{
  "doc_id": "12893",
  "text": "Currently, there are a number of ways to control the growth of pathogenic microorganisms in food products. One of the ways is the use of essential oils (EOs). EOs are aromatic oily extracts obtained from different parts of plants, such as flowers, leaves, wood, bark, roots, seeds, or peel, which exhibit bactericidal or bacteriostatic properties [CITATION_1] . EOs are considered as natural preservatives for raw or mildly processed food [CITATION_2] . EOs have a wide spectrum of antimicrobial properties. As an antimicrobial agent, EOs destroy both the lipid bi-layer of cell membranes and enzyme systems as well as inactivate the genetic material of bacteria [CITATION_3] .",
